P4 - Code Generation
CS 4880 Compiler Design

DESCRIPTION
    Extends P3 by adding a code generation pass after static semantic analysis.
    The program is parsed into a tree, semantically checked, then the tree is
    walked to emit VM assembly targeting a single-accumulator stack machine.

    Output is written to basename.asm when a file argument is given, or to
    stdout when reading from stdin.

    Lex-only mode (-l flag) emits one line per token instead of running
    the parser, semantic analysis, or code generation.

BUILD
    make
    make clean

    Manual (gcc required):
        gcc -Wall -Wextra -pedantic -std=c11 -g -c lexer.c
        gcc -Wall -Wextra -pedantic -std=c11 -g -c tree.c
        gcc -Wall -Wextra -pedantic -std=c11 -g -c parser.c
        gcc -Wall -Wextra -pedantic -std=c11 -g -c semantics.c
        gcc -Wall -Wextra -pedantic -std=c11 -g -c codegen.c
        gcc -Wall -Wextra -pedantic -std=c11 -g -c P4.c
        gcc -Wall -Wextra -pedantic -std=c11 -g -o P4 P4.o parser.o semantics.o codegen.o tree.o lexer.o

RUN
    ./P4 basename        reads basename.ext, writes basename.asm
    ./P4 < file.ext      reads from stdin, writes assembly to stdout
    ./P4                 reads from stdin (type input, Ctrl+D to end)

    ./P4 -l basename     lex-only mode: prints tokens instead of compiling
    ./P4 -l < file.ext

ERROR / WARNING FORMAT
    LEXICAL ERROR: <detail> line <n>
    SYNTAX ERROR: expected <X>, got '<Y>' (line <n>)
    SEMANTIC ERROR: '<name>' declared more than once
    SEMANTIC ERROR: '<name>' used but not defined
    WARNING: '<name>' defined but never used

GRAMMAR
    <program>    -> go <vars> <block> exit
    <vars>       -> empty | int identifier = integer <varList> :
    <varList>    -> identifier = integer <varList> | empty
    <block>      -> { <vars> <stats> }
    <stats>      -> <stat> <mStat>
    <mStat>      -> empty | <stat> <mStat>
    <stat>       -> <read> | <print> | <block> | <cond> | <loop> | <assign>
    <read>       -> scan identifier :
    <print>      -> output <exp> :
    <cond>       -> cond [ identifier <relational> <exp> ] <stat>
    <loop>       -> loop [ identifier <relational> <exp> ] <stat>
    <assign>     -> set identifier = <exp> :
    <relational> -> ?le | ?ge | ?lt | ?gt | ?ne | ?eq | = = | ;
    <exp>        -> <M> ** <exp> | <M> // <exp> | <M>
    <M>          -> <N> + <M> | <N>
    <N>          -> <R> - <N> | - <N> | <R>
    <R>          -> ( <exp> ) | identifier | integer

TOKEN TYPES (lexer)
    IDTk      identifier: starts with 'x', followed by letters/digits/underscores, max 8 chars
    IntTk     integer: decimal digits only, max 8 digits
    KW_tk     keyword: go og loop int exit scan output cond then set func program
    OpTk      multi-char operator: ?le ?ge ?lt ?gt ?ne ?eq ** //
    OpDelTk   single-char operator or delimiter: + - : ; = ( ) { } [ ]
    EOFTk     end of input

    Comments (@text@) are consumed silently; no whitespace allowed inside.

VM TARGET LANGUAGE
    Single-accumulator assembly. All values end up in ACC after expression
    evaluation. Storage is global; variables and compiler temporaries are
    emitted as storage directives after the STOP instruction.

    Instruction set used:
        LOAD  arg       ACC = arg (variable name or integer literal)
        STORE var       var = ACC
        ADD   arg       ACC = ACC + arg
        SUB   arg       ACC = ACC - arg
        MULT  arg       ACC = ACC * arg
        DIV   arg       ACC = ACC / arg
        READ  var       var = keyboard input
        WRITE arg       print arg to output
        BR    label     unconditional jump
        BRNEG label     branch if ACC < 0
        BRZNEG label    branch if ACC <= 0
        BRPOS label     branch if ACC > 0
        BRZPOS label    branch if ACC >= 0
        BRZERO label    branch if ACC == 0
        NOOP            no operation
        STOP            end program

    Output file format:
        [instructions]
        STOP
        varname initialvalue    (one per user variable and compiler temporary)

    Compiler temporaries are named t0, t1, t2, ...
    Branch labels are named L0, L1, L2, ...

TEST FILES
    tests/test_good*.ext   syntactically and semantically valid programs
    tests/test_bad*.ext    programs with syntax errors
    tests/p3gg*.ext        semantic good cases (no errors or expected warnings)
    tests/p3gb*.ext        semantic bad cases (duplicate def, undefined use, unused var)

EXAMPLE
    Input (tests/test_good5.ext):
        go
        int x = 1 :
        { int x1 = 1 :
          scan x :
          set x1 = x + 2 :
          output x1 :
        }
        exit

    Output (tests/test_good5.asm):
        READ x
        LOAD x
        STORE t0
        LOAD 2
        ADD t0
        STORE x1
        LOAD x1
        STORE t1
        WRITE t1
        STOP
        x 1
        x1 1
        t0 0
        t1 0
